Meridian —Dr.
Troy, Ala., has been called as pastor
of the First Baptist church here to
succeed the late Dr. T. J. Shipman.
and Dr. E. S. Pool, who has been sup-

been called as pastor of the Fifteenth
R. J. Bateman of

Avenue Baptist church, to succeed
Rey. E. D. Solomon, who resigned to
accept the position of Baptist pastor-
ate at Camp Shelby, Hattiesburg.

Natchez—The campaign in the in-
terest of war savings by the purchase
of thrift stamps and war savings cer-
tificates is well under way and much
interest is being manifested here. The
work is being done through schools
and all who have accepted agencies
for the stamps are joining in the et-
fort to make Natchez and Adams coun-
ty lead the state.

Jackson.—Arthur Taylor, of Mont-
gomery county, was among the sol-
diers of the English army reported 4
month ago as “wounded and missing,”
and so far he nas not been heard from
by his relatives on this side. He is a
twin brother of Chancellor O. B. Tay-
lor of Jackson, and the latter is mak-
ing every possible effort to get news
as to his present whereabouts.

three banks of Yazoo City of $1,397,-
536.26 more Dec. 31, 1917, than Dee.
31, 1916, and a total gain of $1,185,-
473.12 in the same period in deposits
subject to check, gives a very good
idea of the prosperity of Yazoo county
during the year of 1917. '

first pamphlet delivered by them is

of Ocean Springs were elected at a
meeting of the organization, as fol-
lows: President, Dr. Charles Dodge
of Boulder, Col.; secretary, Dr. E. H.
Deyoe of Neeish, Mich.; treasurer, J.
A. Witty of Whitehall, Mich.

Greenwaod.—Mrs. B. E. Green of the
Mississippi Finding association has
brought nine orphans of that institu-
tion to the Hotel Irving, where she is
stopping, and announced that these
nine children were seeking a warm
home, temporarily, at least.

Crystal Springs.—Since the “bone
dry” law has gone into effect, liquor
is costing the consumer $8 per pint
when purchased from the “blind ti-
gers,” and antiseptic has become a
popular substitute for whiskey.

Natchez.—C. E. Topper, alleged la-
bor agent, who claimed to be a repre-
sentative of the government in indwe-
ing labor to leave this section, has
been released from jail on bond pend-
ing his trial, which is set for Jan. 26.

days at Camp Shelby was reported
when Private Arthur Hunt of Port-
land, Ind., died of pneumonia. Health
conditions at camp here are excep-
tionally good.

Memphis delivered two addresses

The opponents of the state tax com-
mission received their first jolt when
the house committee on ways and
means by a vote of 15 to 2 ordered an
adverse report on the Watts bill to
repeal the law creating the tax com-
mission. This vote in committee in-
dicates that the opponents of the tax
commission are losing ground in the
legislature and that they are in a ml-
nority.

The house joint judiciary committee
has brought in a favorable repori on
the bill introduced by Representative
W E. Mcintyre, of Rankin, known as
a “corrupt practice act.” The bill lim:
its the amount of money that can be
spent by all candidates for public of:
fice in this state for campaign pur-
poses.

The only feature of the bill that has
encountered any serious opposition is
the provision regulating the campalgn
expenditures of candidates for county
offices. Mr. McIntyre has indicated
that he might be willing to eliminate
that portion of the bill, thus making
the measure apply only to state, con-
gressional and district offices.

lectors in which to make their setéle- |

New County Proposal Opposed.

The question of a new county with
Belzoni, the county seat, and taking a
part of Yazoo county, is again to be
before the legislature. The people of
Yazoo county are not willing to sur-
render an acre, it is sald, and will
fight for every inch of land to stay
within Yazoo's boundaries.
Leprosy Found in Harrison County.

The Mississippi health authorities
will soon have to deal in a serious
way with the leprosy problem. The
monthly morbidity report of the state
health board shows another case of,
leprosy in Harrison county.

This is the second case reported
from that county recently. Both pa-
tients are now under guard, and are
soon to be sent to the Lepers’ Home
in Louisiana, arrangements with this

ens in view having been made with
the health authorities of tiat state. |

Doctor Royston’s Rabbit.

Dr. Barney Royston of Evansville
was out hunting near his home, re-
lates the Indianapolis News, and shot
a rabbit in the back yard at the home
of one of his neighbors. Just as he
started to get it, the little daughter
of the neighbor ran out and picked it
up.

“Wait,” Doctor Royston said, “that’s
my rabbit. I shot it.”

“I know, but you shot {t In our
yard,” the child answered. She hesi-
tated a moment and then sid:

“Wait, I don’t want you tn lose any-
thing by it.”

She took the rabbit Into the house
and came out With something in her
hand,

“This is yours,” she sald as she
handed Doctor Royston a shell for his
un.
